CPU Operator v1.0 — Syntax, Semantics, and Parser Sketch

Purpose

The CPU Operator is a proposed formalism for expressing conditioned equivalence:
	•	C = Context
	•	P = Perspective
	•	U = Uncertainty

Instead of flattening claims into unconditional equality, CPU notation preserves the frame under which a claim is being made.

⸻

Core Form

A ≈ B ⟨C, P, U⟩

Read as:

A is approximately or operationally equivalent to B under context C, from perspective P, with uncertainty U.

⸻

Minimal Syntax

Canonical form

<lemma_left> ≈ <lemma_right> ⟨<context>, <perspective>, <uncertainty>⟩

Example

dog ≈ wolf ⟨taxonomic frame, biological observer, 0.88⟩


⸻

Semantic Roles

1. Left Expression (A)

The first entity, claim, model, or state.

Examples:
	•	dog
	•	policy_A
	•	light_wave
	•	system_state_t1

2. Right Expression (B)

The compared entity, claim, model, or state.

Examples:
	•	wolf
	•	policy_B
	•	light_particle
	•	system_state_t2

3. Context (C)

The frame, assumptions, or domain under which the comparison holds.

Examples:
	•	taxonomic frame
	•	economic recession
	•	measurement setup
	•	high-noise environment

4. Perspective (P)

The observer, agent, interpretive lens, or evaluation standpoint.

Examples:
	•	biological observer
	•	worker perspective
	•	instrument model
	•	human annotator

5. Uncertainty (U)

Confidence, belief strength, precision, or resolution.

Examples:
	•	0.88
	•	0.62
	•	low
	•	interval(0.70,0.84)

⸻

Formal Grammar (EBNF-style)

cpu_expr     ::= expr ws? approx_op ws? expr ws? cpu_suffix
approx_op    ::= "≈"
cpu_suffix   ::= "⟨" ws? context ws? "," ws? perspective ws? "," ws? uncertainty ws? "⟩"

expr         ::= atom | identifier | quoted_string
context      ::= value
perspective  ::= value
uncertainty  ::= number | identifier | interval

value        ::= identifier | quoted_string
interval     ::= "interval(" number "," number ")"

identifier   ::= (letter | "_") (letter | digit | "_" | "-" | " ")*

number       ::= digit+ ("." digit+)?

quoted_string ::= '"' char* '"'

ws           ::= (" " | "\t")+


