⸻

Semantic Interpretation Rules

Rule 1: Conditionality

A CPU statement is never treated as unconditional identity.

A ≈ B ⟨C, P, U⟩  ≠  A = B

Rule 2: Frame Dependence

If context changes, equivalence strength may change.

dog ≈ wolf ⟨taxonomic frame, biological observer, 0.88⟩
dog ≈ wolf ⟨domestic companionship frame, pet owner, 0.41⟩

Both can be valid without contradiction.

Rule 3: Perspective Sensitivity

A claim may remain stable across contexts but vary by observer model.

risk_low ≈ acceptable ⟨regulated environment, compliance officer, 0.82⟩
risk_low ≈ acceptable ⟨startup environment, founder, 0.57⟩

Rule 4: Uncertainty is Native

Uncertainty is part of the expression, not a footnote.

Rule 5: Non-Relativistic Constraint

CPU expressions do not imply “anything can mean anything.”
They formalize conditioned claims, not arbitrary ones.

⸻

Optional Extended Forms

A. Strong equivalence

Use ≡ when equivalence is definitional under a frame.

morning_star ≡ venus ⟨astronomical reference frame, modern observer, 0.99⟩

B. Weak similarity

Use ~ for loose resemblance.

poem_A ~ poem_B ⟨emotional tone, reader perspective, 0.68⟩

C. Directed transformation

Use → when relation is asymmetric.

raw_signal → interpreted_signal ⟨translation pipeline, classifier perspective, 0.76⟩


⸻

Suggested Operator Family

=    exact equality
≈    approximate / operational equivalence
≡    definitional / structural equivalence
~    resemblance / affinity
→    transformation
⟨C,P,U⟩  conditioning suffix


⸻

Inference Heuristics

These are not strict proofs yet, but useful operating rules.

1. Context match strengthens comparison

If two CPU expressions share the same context and perspective, they are more directly comparable.

2. Divergent context weakens direct comparison

Claims with very different contexts should not be merged without translation.

3. Uncertainty composes conservatively

When chaining claims, confidence should not increase automatically.

Example:

A ≈ B ⟨C1, P1, 0.90⟩
B ≈ C ⟨C1, P1, 0.80⟩

A conservative chained estimate might be:

A ≈ C ⟨C1, P1, 0.72⟩

Simple default rule:

U_chain = U1 * U2

This is only a starter heuristic.

